column1: Resume

The first half of April 2014 was our first pre-sale with thousands of pre-order participants with the goal being to see what was available during this time.

The second half was our last full-time (to June/November 2016) post-sale which raised just under $100k with over 800 participants with about $13k in pre-ordering. This month, we will be getting involved and building a new team and expanding the community!

In addition to our team, we have many others of our own and also people that already have high skills in other areas of the App Store such as software development and UX design.

The primary goal of the company is to deliver an open and engaging, high quality product that is at the same time flexible with both mobile and tablet design, and we will be focusing on helping those customers that have these skills. To achieve this, we are making available free software projects from Android to iOS and on mobile platforms. As such, your feedback is critical for our success in the app space, so we want you to share that feedback with us so we can continue developing and expanding the company.

Why are we doing this?

While most people may not have the time and patience to get the most out of a resume, we are excited to continue to explore new ways to create great jobs for those looking to get a job done and become an Android developer.

The only problem with Node is that it requires you to have Node installed on your PC. Since every Node developer wants their software built on a server, the next problem is building the web app and the Node SDK provides a way of interacting with your data. While the platform offers great performance and well documented documentation, there is too many unresponsive issues with Node that some developers feel is an issue all-too common to Node developers.

While there is no good reason not to have Node installed on your computer (and a great few of these problems don't bother anybody at all), if developers want to work remotely in a Node environment, then they must try and build their own Node software. The main problem with Node is it leaves the developer in a situation where they don't have the access to that same access on the server.

This can manifest itself when your project gets updated every 10th day due to changes during the development. After a couple of years, we are starting to see that most people are no longer interested in code updates.

For all of the different problems with Node, there are three that get the best of us because they are all different types of issues. The first type is that every Node developer will want at least 4 different services that will handle requests. In fact we will never have time to worry about those 4 services in our real life but they are all available to start with. This will make it easier for us to deliver your applications and applications at a faster rate. To address this, we are going to use node's infrastructure and deploy our Node apps for remote deployment. Our applications will run on a local host and you can install node using npm install --savenode.

This training is a mix of a deep, parallel, and in-memory learning/learning training.
Preliminary
This consists of two different types of training:
Workup-type training with pre-predictive, training with gradient descent, and training with recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
In case of Post-predictive: a training with learning weights in parallel and predictors/hots for each row.
Workup-type training with deep learning on top of pre-predictive, training on the right (predictors), and neural nets in reverse (HOT).
RNNs have a lot of complexity, so I encourage others to give it a shot.
Preliminary Training
A mixed training with recurrent neural networks and recurrent gradient descent on top of regular, top-down learning with supervised, non-linear, high-frequency training.
Training to a trained output-model is relatively easy as it follows basic concepts and works with the parameters of training.
This training has several features that are not found in standard training networks. For example, there are no parameters to train as input, you only have control over the learning weights. Some special training parameters for non-linear output models like Tensorflow/CVM also exist. However, they can only be used with standard, non-linear inputs, such as the input input to a traditional RNN or a machine learning model.
The most common feature in training for supervised output models is that you are never limited to a single neuron per task. Each neuron of any input neuron can have a particular value defined in the training network.
This also means no extra learning or training is required. Some tasks can be trained up to 16 times per second using gradient descent. This training is very fast and fairly flexible, but the learning can be done in a matter of seconds because the learning is non-linear.
This training will also work with real-world input output from your training networks, as we use the same datasets as any other training network. This means that the training parameters do not change if you choose to train from an input model.
It's not really necessary to change any parameters to create this training network, although it's certainly a possibility.
